# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cornhole
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The **American Cornhole League** (**ACL**) is one of the sanctioning bodies for the sport of professional cornhole in the United States.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] Headquartered in Rock Hill, South Carolina, the ACL hosts over 25,000 tournaments per year and has an active player base of over 100,000 players.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The ACL features a group of professional cornhole players each season that compete on television broadcasts (network partners include ESPN and CBS).
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] These players are referred to as ACL Pros.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The ACL is majority owned by ACL Commissioner Stacey Moore.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] In 2021, the ACL introduced its first outside investors of Asland Capital Partners and John Thompson III.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The American Cornhole League (ACL) was founded in 2015 by Stacey Moore, its current Commissioner.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] It established a standard bag for competitive play and partnered with manufacturer AllCornhole for licensed cornhole equipment.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] In 2016 ACL streamed its first competitive event "Championship of Bags" on ESPN3., which began airing in 2017 on ESPN2.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] In 2019 ACL created the nonprofit USA Cornhole to support the sport's growth with the goal of inclusion in the Olympics.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] In 2020 amid the COVID-19 pandemic, the ACL aired on ESPN networks for six straight weeks, propelling exponential growth for the league and sport.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] In 2021, the ACL signed a network contract with CBS Sports, introduced the ACL Pro Shootout Series, and launched the ACL Cornhole TV streaming channel in partnership with Triple-B Media.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] As of 2024, ACL sponsors skill-restricted National Pro Tour competitions (including the World Championships in the fall) and unrestricted Open events.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] Players are able to improve their standings and potentially qualify for Pro competitions by participating in State, Regional, and Local Open events.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] Skill levels are determined by average Points Per Round (PPG), consisting of Advanced (PPG >= 8), Competitive (PPG 7-8), Intermediate (PPG 6-7), Novice (PPG <6).
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The American Cornhole League has specific rules on how they work tournaments.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] Some of these rules are what kinds of bags and boards that can be used.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] Both boards and bags have to be stamped with the ACL logo on it to be considered regulation.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] With having the stamp put on it shows the bags and boards are the right weight and length.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] In other cases some of the ACL rules can be flawed for example players keeping their own score, this can lead to cheating.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] To solve the cheating is to have AST keep the scores instead of the players manually keeping it (Overturf).
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] By solving this issue it prevents games and even tournaments from being replayed (Gillespie).
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The ACL relies on players to be honest with their score but in some cases, the players are not truthful.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The reasoning behind the stamp is to make the game as fair as possible so people do not bring in lighter or heavier bags to cheat.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] Another rule they have is that the boards have to be 27 feet apart from the front of the boards.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The boards in the American Cornhole league have to be stamped just like the bags so no one can bring a slow or slick board to tournaments and have an advantage over their competition.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] The ACL Teams division is composed of sixteen teams divided into four regions within two divisions.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-league] There are also minor league teams, akin to a farm system in baseball, which each span a few states.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] The **American Cornhole Organization** (**ACO**) was founded in 2005 by Frank Geers for the purpose of transforming the game of cornhole, often played recreationally for fun, into a competitive National Sport.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] In December 2006, American Cornhole Organization held its first ACO Nationals Championship in Northern Kentucky.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] The ACO was established in 2005 to standardize cornhole equipment and cornhole rules.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] Headquartered in Camp Dennison, Ohio, the ACO relies on a network of ACO Certified Officials to facilitate sanctioning ACO Majors, Pro Series Tours, ACO Cornhole Tournaments and ACO Cornhole Leagues across the United States and Europe.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] In the early days of its foundation, the ACO established standardization of cornhole board, bag, and rules in ACO sanctioned cornhole events.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] In 2005, the ACO developed a line of cornhole products and a platform for cornhole rules, handicapping, player rankings, and league and tournament structures under the umbrella of the ACO Governing Body for the Sport of Cornhole.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] Prior to the first ACO Nationals, the American Cornhole Organization held various organized ACO cornhole tournaments and events, including the Carson Palmer Cornhole Classic in Cincinnati in June 2006.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] In 2006, The ACO held its first ACO Nationals Championship in Northern Kentucky to crown the ACO Nationals King of Cornhole.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] The same year, the ACO introduced a resin fill beg at its Nationals Championship, replacing the standard corn fill bag.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] The resin-fill bag has become widely adopted in the sport.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] The ACO introduced standardized and sanctioned equipment to the game including ACO Star Logo Cornhole Boards, ACO Soft Touch Resin Fill Cornhole Bags, and ACO Governing Body Sport of Cornhole Rules.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] Structure and consistency gave legitimacy to cornhole as a sport, which helps ACO spread professional cornhole on a national scale.
[src:cornhole/american-cornhole-organization] In 2009 the ACO introduced the PlayersChoice Cornhole Bag - a bag with a two-sided playing surface, which added complexity to the sport.
[src:cornhole/bean-bag] A **bean bag** (also **beanbag**) is a sealed bag containing dried beans, PVC pellets, expanded polystyrene, or expanded polypropylene.
[src:cornhole/bean-bag] The bags are commonly used for throwing games, but they have various other applications.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was incorporated as a city in 1837 near a portage between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It grew rapidly in the mid-19th century.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed several square miles and left more than 100,000 homeless, but Chicago's population continued to grow.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago made noted contributions to urban planning and architecture, such as the Chicago School, the development of the City Beautiful movement, and the steel-framed skyscraper.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is an international hub for finance, culture, commerce, industry, education, technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It has the largest and most diverse finance derivatives market in the world, generating 20% of all volume in commodities and financial futures alone.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] O'Hare International Airport is routinely ranked among the world's top ten busiest airports by passenger traffic, and the region is also the nation's railroad hub.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago area has one of the highest gross domestic products (GDP) of any urban region in the world, ranking sixth globally, generating over $919 billion in 2024.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's economy is diverse, with no single industry employing more than 14% of the workforce.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is a major destination for tourism, with nearly 57 million people visiting its cultural institutions, Lake Michigan beaches, restaurants, and other tourist sites in 2025.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's culture has made significant contributions to the visual arts, literature, film, theater, comedy (especially improvisational comedy), food, dance, and music (particularly jazz, blues, soul, hip-hop, gospel, industrial, and electronic dance music, especially house music).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and the Lyric Opera of Chicago, while the Art Institute of Chicago has an influential visual arts museum and art school.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago area is home to the University of Chicago, Northwestern University, and the University of Illinois Chicago, among other institutions of higher education.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It also hosts the Barack Obama Presidential Center.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Professional sports in Chicago include all major professional leagues, including two Major League Baseball teams.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city also hosts the Chicago Marathon, one of the World Marathon Majors.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The name *Chicago* is derived from a French rendering of the indigenous Miami–Illinois word *šikaakwa*, which was a name for a wild relative of onion and garlic known to modern botanists as *Allium tricoccum*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The first known reference to the site of the city of Chicago as "*Checagou*" was by Robert de La Salle around 1679 in a memoir.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Henri Joutel, in his journal of 1688, noted that the eponymous wild "garlic" grew profusely in the area.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city has had several nicknames throughout its history, such as the Windy City, Chi-Town, Second City, and City of the Big Shoulders.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the mid-18th century, the area was inhabited by the Potawatomi, an indigenous tribe who had succeeded the Miami, Sauk and Meskwaki peoples in this region.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The first known permanent settler in Chicago was a trader, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Du Sable was of African descent, perhaps born in the French colony of Saint-Domingue (Haiti), and he established the settlement in the 1780s.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] He is commonly known as the "Founder of Chicago".
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1795, following the victory of the new United States in the Northwest Indian War, an area that was to be part of Chicago was turned over to the U.S. for a military post by native tribes in accordance with the Treaty of Greenville.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Army constructed Fort Dearborn, which was destroyed during the War of 1812 in the Battle of Fort Dearborn by the Potawatomi before being later rebuilt.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] After the War of 1812, the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi tribes ceded additional land to the United States in the 1816 Treaty of St.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Potawatomi were forcibly removed from their land after the 1833 Treaty of Chicago and sent west of the Mississippi River as part of the federal policy of Indian removal.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] On August 12, 1833, the Town of Chicago was organized with a population of about 200.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Within seven years it grew to more than 6,000 people.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] On June 15, 1835, the first public land sales began with Edmund Dick Taylor as Receiver of Public Monies.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The City of Chicago was incorporated on Saturday, March 4, 1837, and for several decades was the world's fastest-growing city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] As the site of the Chicago Portage, the city became an important transportation hub between the eastern and western United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's first railway, Galena and Chicago Union Railroad, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal opened in 1848.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The canal allowed steamboats and sailing ships on the Great Lakes to connect to the Mississippi River.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A flourishing economy brought residents from rural communities and immigrants from abroad.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Manufacturing and retail and finance sectors became dominant, influencing the American economy.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago Board of Trade (established 1848) listed the first-ever standardized "exchange-traded" forward contracts, which were called futures contracts.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the 1850s, Chicago gained national political prominence as the home of Senator Stephen Douglas, the champion of the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the "popular sovereignty" approach to the issue of the spread of slavery.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] These issues also helped propel another Illinoisan, Abraham Lincoln, to the national stage.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Lincoln was nominated in Chicago for U.S. president at the 1860 Republican National Convention, which was held in a purpose-built auditorium called the Wigwam.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] He defeated Douglas in the general election, and this set the stage for the American Civil War.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] To accommodate rapid population growth and demand for better sanitation, the city improved its infrastructure.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In February 1856, Chicago's Common Council approved Chesbrough's plan to build the United States' first comprehensive sewerage system.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The project raised much of central Chicago to a new grade with the use of jackscrews for raising buildings.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] While elevating Chicago, and at first improving the city's health, the untreated sewage and industrial waste now flowed into the Chicago River, and subsequently into Lake Michigan, polluting the city's primary freshwater source.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city responded by tunneling two miles (3.2 km) out into Lake Michigan to newly built water cribs.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1900, the problem of sewage contamination was largely resolved when the city completed a major engineering feat.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It reversed the flow of the Chicago River so that the water flowed away from Lake Michigan rather than into it.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] This project began with the construction and improvement of the Illinois and Michigan Canal, and was completed with the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal that connects to the Illinois River, which flows into the Mississippi River.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] On October 8, 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6.4 km) long and 1-mile (1.6 km) wide, a large section of the city at the time.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] At least 300 people were killed and over 100,000 were left homeless from the fire.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] However, much of the city, including railroads and stockyards, survived intact, and from the ruins of the previous wooden structures arose more modern constructions of steel and stone.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] These set a precedent for worldwide construction.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] During its rebuilding period, Chicago constructed the world's first skyscraper in 1885, using steel-skeleton construction.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Labor conflicts followed the industrial boom and the rapid expansion of the labor pool during the Gilded Age, including the Haymarket affair on May 4, 1886, and in 1894 the Pullman Strike.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Anarchist and socialist groups played prominent roles in creating very large and highly organized labor actions.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Concern for social problems among Chicago's immigrant poor led Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr to found Hull House in 1889.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Programs that were developed there became a model for the new field of social work.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] During the 1870s and 1880s, Chicago attained national stature as the leader in the movement to improve public health.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] City laws and later, state laws that upgraded standards for the medical profession and fought urban epidemics of cholera, smallpox, and yellow fever were both passed and enforced.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] These laws became templates for public health reform in other cities and states.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city established many large, well-landscaped municipal parks, which also included public sanitation facilities.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The chief advocate for improving public health in Chicago was John H.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Rauch established a plan for Chicago's park system in 1866.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] He created Lincoln Park by closing a cemetery filled with shallow graves, and in 1867, in response to an outbreak of cholera he helped establish a new Chicago Board of Health.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Ten years later, he became the secretary and then the president of the first Illinois State Board of Health, which carried out most of its activities in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the 1800s, Chicago became the nation's railroad hub, and by 1910 over 20 railroads operated passenger service out of six different downtown terminals.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1883, Chicago's railway managers needed a general time convention, so they developed the standardized system of North American time zones.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] This system for telling time spread throughout the continent.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The desire to join the city was driven by municipal services that the city could provide its residents.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1893, Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition on former marshland at the present location of Jackson Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Exposition drew 27.5 million visitors, and is considered the most influential world's fair in history.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city's municipal device, a Y within a circle, was the result of a contest run by the *Chicago Tribune* in 1892, in anticipation of the Columbian Exposition.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The University of Chicago, formerly at another location, moved to the same South Side location in 1892.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The term "midway" for a fair or carnival referred originally to the Midway Plaisance, a strip of park land that still runs through the University of Chicago campus and connects the Washington and Jackson Parks.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's flourishing economy attracted huge numbers of new immigrants from Europe and migrants from the Eastern United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Of the total population in 1900, more than 77% were either foreign-born or born in the United States of foreign parentage.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Germans, Irish, Poles, Swedes, and Czechs made up nearly two-thirds of the foreign-born population (by 1900, whites were 98.1% of the city's population).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] During World War I and the 1920s there was a major expansion in industry.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the Southern United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Between 1910 and 1930, the African American population of Chicago increased dramatically, from 44,103 to 233,903.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] This Great Migration had an immense cultural impact, called the Chicago Black Renaissance, part of the New Negro Movement, in art, literature, and music.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Continuing racial tensions and violence in the city, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919, also occurred.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The ratification of the 18th amendment to the Constitution in 1919 made the production and sale (including exportation) of alcoholic beverages illegal in the United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] This ushered in the beginning of what is known as the gangster era, a time that roughly spans from 1919 until 1933 when Prohibition was repealed.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The 1920s saw gangsters, including Al Capone, Dion O'Banion, Bugs Moran and Tony Accardo battle law enforcement and each other on the streets of Chicago during the Prohibition era.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was the location of the infamous St.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Valentine's Day Massacre in 1929, when Al Capone sent men to gun down members of a rival gang, North Side, led by Bugs Moran, leaving seven rival members dead.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] From 1920 to 1921, the city was affected by a series of tenant rent strikes, which led to the formation of the Chicago Tenants Protective association, passage of the Kessenger tenant laws, and of a heat ordinance that legally required flats to be kept above 68 °F during winter months by landlords.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was the first American city to have a homosexual-rights organization.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The organization, formed in 1924, was called the Society for Human Rights.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It produced the first American publication for homosexuals, *Friendship and Freedom*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Police and political pressure caused the organization to disband.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Great Depression brought unprecedented suffering to Chicago, in no small part due to the city's heavy reliance on heavy industry.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Notably, industrial areas on the south side and neighborhoods lining both branches of the Chicago River were devastated; by 1933 over 50% of industrial jobs in the city had been lost, and unemployment rates amongst blacks and Latinos in the city were over 40%.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Republican political machine in Chicago was utterly destroyed by the economic crisis, and every mayor since 1931 has been a Democrat.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] From 1928 to 1933, the city witnessed a tax revolt, and the city was unable to meet payroll or provide relief efforts.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The fiscal crisis was resolved by 1933, and at the same time, federal relief funding began to flow into Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was also a hotbed of labor activism, with Unemployed Councils contributing heavily in the early depression to create solidarity for the poor and demand relief; these organizations were created by socialist and communist groups.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By 1935, the Workers Alliance of America began organizing the poor, workers, the unemployed.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the spring of 1937 Republic Steel Works witnessed the Memorial Day massacre of 1937 in the neighborhood of East Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1933, Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak was fatally wounded in Miami, Florida, during a failed assassination attempt on President-elect Franklin D.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1933 and 1934, the city celebrated its centennial by hosting the Century of Progress International Exposition World's Fair.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The theme of the fair was technological innovation over the century since Chicago's founding.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] During World War II, the city of Chicago alone produced more steel than the United Kingdom every year from 1939 – 1945, and more than Nazi Germany from 1943 – 1945.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Great Migration, which had been on pause due to the Depression, resumed at an even faster pace in the second wave, as hundreds of thousands of blacks from the South arrived in the city to work in the steel mills, railroads, and shipping yards.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] On December 2, 1942, physicist Enrico Fermi conducted the world's first controlled nuclear reaction at the University of Chicago as part of the top-secret Manhattan Project.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] This led to the creation of the atomic bomb by the United States, which it used in World War II in 1945.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Daley, a Democrat, was elected in 1955, in the era of machine politics.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1956, the city conducted its last major expansion when it annexed the land under O'Hare airport, including a small portion of DuPage County.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By the 1960s, white residents in several neighborhoods left the city for the suburban areas – in many American cities, a process known as white flight – as Blacks continued to move beyond the Black Belt.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] While home loan discriminatory redlining against blacks continued, the real estate industry practiced what became known as blockbusting, completely changing the racial composition of whole neighborhoods.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Structural changes in industry, such as globalization and job outsourcing, caused heavy job losses for lower-skilled workers.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] At its peak during the 1960s, some 250,000 workers were employed in the steel industry in Chicago, but the steel crisis of the 1970s and 1980s reduced this number to just 28,000 in 2015.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1966, Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Raby led the Chicago Freedom Movement, which culminated in agreements between Mayor Richard J.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Two years later, the city hosted the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention, which featured physical confrontations both inside and outside the convention hall, with anti-war protesters, journalists and bystanders being beaten by police.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Major construction projects, including the Sears Tower (now known as the Willis Tower, which in 1974 became the world's tallest building), University of Illinois at Chicago, McCormick Place, and O'Hare International Airport, were undertaken during Richard J.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1979, Jane Byrne, the city's first female mayor, was elected.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] She was notable for temporarily moving into the crime-ridden Cabrini-Green housing project and leading Chicago's school system out of a financial crisis.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1983, Harold Washington became the first black mayor of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Washington's first term in office directed attention to poor and previously neglected minority neighborhoods.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] He was re‑elected in 1987 but died of a heart attack soon after.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Washington was succeeded by 6th ward alderperson Eugene Sawyer, who was elected by the Chicago City Council and served until a special election.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] His accomplishments included improvements to parks and creating incentives for sustainable development, as well as closing Meigs Field in the middle of the night and destroying the runways.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] After successfully running for re-election five times, and becoming Chicago's longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Daley declined to run for a seventh term.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1992, a construction accident near the Kinzie Street Bridge produced a breach connecting the Chicago River to a tunnel below, which was part of an abandoned freight tunnel system extending throughout the downtown Loop district.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The tunnels filled with 250 million US gallons (1,000,000 m3) of water, affecting buildings throughout the district and forcing a shutdown of electrical power.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The area was shut down for three days and some buildings did not reopen for weeks; losses were estimated at $1.95 billion.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] On February 23, 2011, Rahm Emanuel, a former White House Chief of Staff and member of the House of Representatives, won the mayoral election.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Emanuel was sworn in as mayor on May 16, 2011, and won re-election in 2015.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Lori Lightfoot, the city's first African American woman mayor and its first openly LGBTQ mayor, was elected to succeed Emanuel as mayor in 2019.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] All three city-wide elective offices were held by women (and women of color) for the first time in Chicago history: in addition to Lightfoot, the city clerk was Anna Valencia and the city treasurer was Melissa Conyears-Ervin.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] On May 15, 2023, Brandon Johnson assumed office as the 57th mayor of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is located in northeastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of freshwater Lake Michigan.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in both the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city rests on a continental divide at the site of the Chicago Portage, connecting the Mississippi River and the Great Lakes watersheds.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In addition to it lying beside Lake Michigan, two rivers—the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side—flow either entirely or partially through the city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's history and economy are closely tied to its proximity to Lake Michigan.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] While the Chicago River historically handled much of the region's waterborne cargo, today's huge lake freighters use the city's Lake Calumet Harbor on the South Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The lake also provides another positive effect: moderating Chicago's climate, making waterfront neighborhoods slightly warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] When Chicago was founded in 1837, most of the early building was around the mouth of the Chicago River, as can be seen on a map of the city's original 58 blocks.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The overall grade of the city's central, built-up areas is relatively consistent with the natural flatness of its overall natural geography, generally exhibiting only slight differentiation otherwise.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The average land elevation is 579 ft (176.5 m) above sea level.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] While measurements vary somewhat, the lowest points are along the lake shore at 578 ft (176.2 m), while the highest point, at 672 ft (205 m), is the morainal ridge of Blue Island in the city's far south side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Lake Shore Drive runs adjacent to a large portion of Chicago's waterfront.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Some of the parks along the waterfront include Lincoln Park, Grant Park, Burnham Park, and Jackson Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] There are 24 public beaches across 26 miles (42 km) of the waterfront.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Landfill extends into portions of the lake providing space for Navy Pier, Northerly Island, the Museum Campus, and large portions of the McCormick Place Convention Center.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Most of the city's high-rise commercial and residential buildings are close to the waterfront.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] An informal name for the entire Chicago metropolitan area is "Chicagoland", which generally means the city and all its suburbs, though different organizations have slightly different definitions.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Major sections of the city include the central business district, called the Loop, and the North, South, and West Sides.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The North Side is the city's most densely populated residential section, and many high-rises are on this side of the city along the lakefront.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The South Side is the city's largest section, encompassing roughly 60% of its land area.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The South Side contains most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the late 1920s, sociologists at the University of Chicago subdivided the city into 75 distinct community areas, plus O'Hare in 1956 and Edgewater in 1980 for a total of 77.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The community areas can further be subdivided into over 200 informally defined neighborhoods.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's streets were laid out in a street grid that grew from the city's original townsite plot, which was bounded by Lake Michigan on the east, North Avenue on the north, Wood Street on the west, and 22nd Street on the south.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Streets following the Public Land Survey System section lines later became arterial streets in outlying sections.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] As new additions to the city were platted, city ordinance required them to be laid out with eight streets to the mile in one direction and sixteen in the other direction, about one street per 200 meters in one direction and one street per 100 meters in the other direction.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The grid's regularity provided an efficient means of developing new real estate property.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A scattering of diagonal streets, many of them originally Native American trails, also cross the city (Elston, Milwaukee, Ogden, Lincoln, etc.).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Many additional diagonal streets were recommended in the Plan of Chicago, but only the extension of Ogden Avenue was ever constructed.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 2021, Chicago was ranked the fourth-most walkable large city in the United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Many of the city's residential streets have a wide patch of grass or trees between the street and the sidewalk itself.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] This helps to keep pedestrians on the sidewalk further away from the street traffic.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's Western Avenue is the longest continuous urban street in the world.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Other notable streets include Michigan Avenue, State Street, 95th Street, Cicero Avenue, Clark Street, and Belmont Avenue.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The City Beautiful movement inspired Chicago's boulevards and parkways.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The destruction caused by the Great Chicago Fire led to the largest building boom in the history of the nation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1885, the first steel-framed high-rise building, the Home Insurance Building, rose in the city as Chicago ushered in the skyscraper era, which would then be followed by many other cities around the world.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Today, Chicago's skyline is among the world's tallest and densest.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Some of the United States' tallest towers are located in Chicago; Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) is the third tallest building in the Western Hemisphere after One World Trade Center, and Central Park Tower.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Loop's historic buildings include the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Fine Arts Building, 35 East Wacker, and the Chicago Building, 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments by Mies van der Rohe.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Many other architects have left their impression on the Chicago skyline such as Daniel Burnham, Louis Sullivan, Charles B.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Merchandise Mart, once the largest building in the world, had its own zip code until 2008, and stands near the junction of the North and South branches of the Chicago River.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Presently, the four tallest buildings in the city are Willis Tower (formerly the Sears Tower, also a building with its own zip code), Trump International Hotel and Tower, the Aon Center (previously the Standard Oil Building), and the John Hancock Center.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Industrial districts, such as some areas on the South Side, the areas along the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal, and the Northwest Indiana area are clustered.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago gave its name to the Chicago School and was home to the Prairie School, two movements in architecture.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Multiple kinds and scales of houses, townhouses, condominiums, and apartment buildings can be found throughout Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Large swaths of the city's residential areas away from the lake are characterized by brick bungalows built from the early 20th century through the end of World War II.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is also a prominent center of the Polish Cathedral style of church architecture.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago suburb of Oak Park was home to famous architect Frank Lloyd Wright, who had designed The Robie House located near the University of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A popular tourist activity is to take an architecture boat tour along the Chicago River.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is famous for its outdoor public art with donors establishing funding for such art as far back as Benjamin Ferguson's 1905 trust.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A number of Chicago's public art works are by modern figurative artists.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Some events which shaped the city's history have also been memorialized by art works, including the Great Northern Migration (Saar) and the centennial of statehood for Illinois.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Finally, two fountains near the Loop also function as monumental works of art: Plensa's Crown Fountain as well as Burnham and Bennett's Buckingham Fountain.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city mostly lies within the typical hot-summer humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*), and experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with frequent heat waves.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The July daily average temperature is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C), with afternoon temperatures peaking at 84.5 °F (29.2 °C).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In a normal summer, temperatures reach at least 90 °F (32 °C) on 17 days, with lakefront locations staying cooler when winds blow off the lake.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Blizzards do occur, such as in winter 2011.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The normal winter high from December through March is about 36 °F (2 °C).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] January and February are the coldest months.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A polar vortex in January 2019 nearly broke the city's cold record of −27 °F (−33 °C), which was set on January 20, 1985.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Measurable snowfall can continue through the first or second week of April.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, short seasons, typically with low humidity.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Dew point temperatures in the summer range from an average of 55.8 °F (13.2 °C) in June to 61.7 °F (16.5 °C) in July.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] They can reach nearly 80 °F (27 °C), such as during the July 2019 heat wave.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The city lies within USDA plant hardiness zone 6a, transitioning to 5b in the suburbs.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] According to the National Weather Service, Chicago's highest official temperature reading of 105 °F (41 °C) was recorded on July 24, 1934.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Midway Airport reached 109 °F (43 °C) one day prior and recorded a heat index of 125 °F (52 °C) during the 1995 heatwave.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The lowest official temperature of −27 °F (−33 °C) was recorded on January 20, 1985, at O'Hare Airport.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Most of the city's rainfall is brought by thunderstorms, averaging 38 a year.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The region is prone to severe thunderstorms during the spring and summer which can produce large hail, damaging winds, and occasionally tornadoes.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Notably, the F4 Oak Lawn tornado moved through the South Side of the city on April 21, 1967, moving onto Lake Michigan as a waterspout.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Downtown Chicago was struck by an F3 tornado on May 6, 1876, again moving out over Lake Michigan.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Like other major cities, Chicago experiences an urban heat island, making the city and its suburbs milder than surrounding rural areas, especially at night and in winter.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Northeast winds from wintertime cyclones departing south of the region sometimes bring the city lake-effect snow.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] During its first hundred years, Chicago was one of the fastest-growing cities in the world.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] When founded in 1833, fewer than 200 people had settled on what was then the American frontier.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By the time of its first census, seven years later, the population had reached over 4,000.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the forty years from 1850 to 1890, the city's population grew from slightly under 30,000 to over 1 million.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By the 1890 census, Chicago was the second most populous city in the United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By 1900, it was the fifth largest in the world behind Berlin, Paris, New York, and London, and the largest city founded in the prior century.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Within sixty years of the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, the population went from about 300,000 to over 3 million, and reached its highest ever recorded population of 3.6 million for the 1950 census.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] To these ethnic groups, the basis of the city's industrial working class, were added an additional influx of African Americans from the American South as part of the Great Migration—with Chicago's black population doubling between 1910 and 1920 and doubling again between 1920 and 1930.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago has a significant Bosnian population, many of whom arrived in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, the great majority of African Americans moving to Chicago settled in a so‑called "Black Belt" on the city's South Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A large number of blacks also settled on the West Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By 1930, two-thirds of Chicago's black population lived in sections of the city which were 90% black in racial composition.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Around that time, the block of 4600 Winthrop Avenue in the Uptown neighborhood was the only one in the neighborhood on which African Americans could live or open establishments.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's South Side emerged as United States second-largest urban black concentration, following New York's Harlem.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1990, Chicago's South Side and the adjoining south suburbs constituted the largest black majority region in the entire United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Since the 1980s, Chicago has had a massive exodus of African Americans (primarily from the South and West sides) to its suburbs or outside its metropolitan area.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The above average crime and cost of living were leading reasons for the fast declining African American population in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Most of Chicago's foreign-born population were born in Mexico, Poland or India.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] A 2020 study estimated the total Jewish population of the Chicago metropolitan area, both religious and irreligious, at 319,500.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's population declined in the latter half of the 20th century, from over 3.6 million in 1950 down to under 2.7 million by 2010.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] By the time of the official census count in 1990, it was overtaken by Los Angeles as the United States' second largest city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] It then saw a rise in population for the 2000 census, a decrease in 2010, and another increase for the 2020 census.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] According to U.S. census estimates as of July 2019, Chicago's largest racial or ethnic group is non-Hispanic White at 32.8% of the population, Blacks at 30.1% and the Hispanic population at 29.0% of the population.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago became a "de jure" sanctuary city in 2012 when Mayor Rahm Emanuel and the City Council passed the Welcoming City Ordinance.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Census Bureau's American Community Survey data estimates for 2022, the median income for a household in the city was $70,386, and the per capita income was $45,449.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Male full-time workers had a median income of $68,870 versus $60,987 for females.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] About 17.2% of the population lived below the poverty line.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 2018, Chicago ranked seventh globally for the highest number of ultra-high-net-worth residents with roughly 3,300 residents worth more than $30 million.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Persons who did not report or classify an ancestry were 548,790.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago has the third-largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ) population in the United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Since the 2013 legalization of same-sex marriage in Illinois, over 10,000 same-sex couples have wed in Illinois' Cook County, a majority of them in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is the first U.S. city to have a pro-gay organization and consistently ranks as one of the most LGBTQ-friendly cities in the nation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Lake View and Edgewater are historically the epicenters of LGBTQ culture in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] According to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Chicago (71%), with the city being the fourth-most religious metropolis in the United States after Dallas, Atlanta and Houston.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Roman Catholicism and Protestantism are the largest branches (34% and 35% respectively), followed by Eastern Orthodoxy and Jehovah's Witnesses with 1% each.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago also has a sizable non-Christian population.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Non-Christian groups include Irreligious (22%), Judaism (3%), Islam (2%), Buddhism (1%) and Hinduism (1%).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is the headquarters of several religious denominations, including the Evangelical Covenant Church and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The Fourth Presbyterian Church is one of the largest Presbyterian congregations in the United States based on memberships.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Since the 20th century Chicago has also been the headquarters of the Assyrian Church of the East.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] In 2014 the Catholic Church was the largest individual Christian denomination (34%), with the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago being the largest Catholic jurisdiction.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Evangelical Protestantism form the largest theological Protestant branch (16%), followed by Mainline Protestants (11%), and historically Black churches (8%).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Among denominational Protestant branches, Baptists formed the largest group in Chicago (10%); followed by Nondenominational (5%); Lutherans (4%); and Pentecostals (3%).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Non-Christian faiths accounted for 7% of the religious population in 2014.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Judaism has at least 261,000 adherents which is 3% of the population.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] The first two Parliament of the World's Religions in 1893 and 1993 were held in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Many international religious leaders have visited Chicago, including Mother Teresa, the Dalai Lama and Pope John Paul II in 1979.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p01] Pope Leo XIV was born in Chicago in 1955 and graduated from the Catholic Theological Union in Hyde Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has the third-largest gross metropolitan product in the United States—about $670.5 billion according to September 2017 estimates.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has also been rated as having the most balanced economy in the United States, due to its high level of diversification.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area has the third-largest science and engineering work force of any metropolitan area in the nation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago was the base of commercial operations for industrialists John Crerar, John Whitfield Bunn, Richard Teller Crane, Marshall Field, John Farwell, Julius Rosenwald, and many other commercial visionaries who laid the foundation for Midwestern and global industry.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is a major world financial center, with the second-largest central business district in the United States, following Midtown Manhattan.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is the seat of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, the Bank's Seventh District.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has major financial and futures exchanges, including the Chicago Stock Exchange, the Cboe Global Markets Options Exchange, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (the "Merc"), which is owned, along with the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT), by Chicago's CME Group.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2017, Chicago exchanges traded 4.7 billion in derivatives.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chase Bank has its commercial and retail banking headquarters in Chicago's Chase Tower.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Academically, Chicago has been influential through the Chicago school of economics, which fielded 12 Nobel Prize winners.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city and its surrounding metropolitan area contain the third-largest labor pool in the United States with about 4.63 million workers.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Illinois is home to 66 *Fortune* 1000 companies, including those in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city of Chicago also hosts 12 *Fortune* Global 500 companies and 17 *Financial Times* 500 companies.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city claims three Dow 30 companies: aerospace giant Boeing, which moved its headquarters from Seattle to the Chicago Loop in 2001; McDonald's; and Walgreens Boots Alliance.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] For six consecutive years from 2013 through 2018, Chicago was ranked the nation's top metropolitan area for corporate relocations.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] However, three *Fortune* 500 companies left Chicago in 2022, leaving the city with 35, still second to New York City.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Manufacturing, printing, publishing, and food processing also play major roles in the city's economy.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Several medical products and services companies are based in the Chicago area, including Baxter International, Boeing, Abbott Laboratories, and the Healthcare division of General Electric.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Prominent food companies based in Chicago include the world headquarters of Conagra, Ferrara Candy Company, Kraft Heinz, McDonald's, Mondelez International, and Quaker Oats.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has been a hub of the retail sector since its early development, with Montgomery Ward, Sears, and Marshall Field's.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Today the Chicago metropolitan area is the headquarters of several retailers, including Walgreens, Sears, Ace Hardware, Claire's, ULTA Beauty, and Crate & Barrel.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Tech companies based in the area include CDW, Uber Frieght, Zebra Technologies, Motorola Solutions, Motorola along with regional offices for Google, Salesforce, LinkedIn, and more.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago was also the site of the Schwinn Bicycle Company.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is a major world convention destination.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city's main convention center is McCormick Place.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] With its four interconnected buildings, it is the largest convention center in the nation and third-largest in the world.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] (behind Las Vegas and Orlando) in number of conventions hosted annually.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's minimum wage for non-tipped employees is one of the highest in the nation and reached $15 in 2021.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city's waterfront location and nightlife attracts residents and tourists alike.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Over a third of the city population is concentrated in the lakefront neighborhoods from Rogers Park in the north to South Shore in the south.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has many upscale dining establishments as well as many ethnic restaurant districts.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Downtown is the center of Chicago's financial, cultural, governmental, and commercial institutions and the site of Grant Park and many of the city's skyscrapers.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Many of the city's financial institutions, such as the CBOT and the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, are located within a section of downtown called "The Loop", which is an eight-block by five-block area of city streets that is encircled by elevated rail tracks.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The term "The Loop" is largely used by locals to refer to the entire downtown area as well.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The central area includes the Near North Side, the Near South Side, and the Near West Side, as well as the Loop.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] These areas contribute famous skyscrapers, abundant restaurants, shopping, museums, Soldier Field, convention facilities, parkland, and beaches.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Lincoln Park contains Lincoln Park Zoo and Lincoln Park Conservatory.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The River North Gallery District features the nation's largest concentration of contemporary art galleries outside of New York City.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Lake View is home to Boystown, the city's large LGBT nightlife and culture center.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Pride Parade, held the last Sunday in June, is one of the world's largest with over a million people in attendance.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] North Halsted Street is the main thoroughfare of Boystown.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The South Side neighborhood of Hyde Park is the home of former U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The neighborhood is home to the Barack Obama Presidential Center, a museum and library dedicated to his presidency.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] It also contains the University of Chicago, ranked one of the world's top ten universities, and the Museum of Science and Industry.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The 6-mile (9.7 km) long Burnham Park stretches along the waterfront of the South Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Two of the city's largest parks are also located on this side of the city: Jackson Park, bordering the waterfront, hosted the World's Columbian Exposition in 1893, and is the site of the aforementioned museum; and slightly west sits Washington Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The two parks themselves are connected by a wide strip of parkland called the Midway Plaisance, running adjacent to the University of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The South Side hosts one of the city's largest parades, the annual African American Bud Billiken Parade and Picnic, which travels through Bronzeville to Washington Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Ford Motor Company has an automobile assembly plant on the South Side in Hegewisch, and most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago are also on the South Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The West Side holds the Garfield Park Conservatory, one of the largest collections of tropical plants in any U.S. city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Prominent Latino cultural attractions found here include Humboldt Park's Institute of Puerto Rican Arts and Culture and the annual Puerto Rican People's Parade, as well as the National Museum of Mexican Art and St.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Near West Side holds the University of Illinois at Chicago and was once home to Oprah Winfrey's Harpo Studios, the site of which has been rebuilt as the global headquarters of McDonald's.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city's distinctive accent, made famous by its use in classic films like *The Blues Brothers* and television programs like the *Saturday Night Live* skit "Bill Swerski's Superfans", is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] This dialect can be found in other cities bordering the Great Lakes, such as Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee, and Buffalo, New York, and most prominently features a rearrangement of certain vowel sounds, such as the short "a" sound as in "cat", which can sound more like "kyet" to outsiders.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The accent remains well associated with the city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Renowned Chicago theater companies include the Goodman Theatre in the Loop; the Steppenwolf Theatre Company and Victory Gardens Theater in Lincoln Park; and the Chicago Shakespeare Theater at Navy Pier.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Broadway In Chicago offers Broadway-style entertainment at five theaters: the Nederlander Theatre, CIBC Theatre, Cadillac Palace Theatre, Auditorium Building of Roosevelt University, and Broadway Playhouse at Water Tower Place.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Polish language productions for Chicago's large Polish speaking population can be seen at the historic Gateway Theatre in Jefferson Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Since 1968, the Joseph Jefferson Awards are given annually to acknowledge excellence in theater in the Chicago area.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's theater community spawned modern improvisational theater, and includes the prominent groups The Second City and I.O.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Symphony Orchestra (CSO) performs at Symphony Center, and is recognized as one of the best orchestras in the world.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Also performing regularly at Symphony Center is the Chicago Sinfonietta, a more diverse and multicultural counterpart to the CSO.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In the summer, many outdoor concerts are given in Grant Park and Millennium Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Ravinia Festival, located 25 miles (40 km) north of Chicago, is the summer home of the CSO, and is a favorite destination for many Chicagoans.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Civic Opera House is home to the Lyric Opera of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Lithuanian Opera Company of Chicago was founded by Lithuanian Chicagoans in 1956, and presents operas in Lithuanian.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Joffrey Ballet and Chicago Festival Ballet perform in various venues, including the Harris Theater in Millennium Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has several other contemporary and jazz dance troupes, such as the Hubbard Street Dance Chicago and Chicago Dance Crash.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Other live-music genre which are part of the city's cultural heritage include Chicago blues, Chicago soul, jazz, and gospel.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is the birthplace of house music (a popular form of electronic dance music) and industrial music, and is the site of an influential hip hop scene.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In the 1980s and 90s, the city was the global center for house and industrial music, two forms of music created in Chicago, as well as being popular for alternative rock, punk, and new wave.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has been a center for rave culture, since the 1980s.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A flourishing independent rock music culture brought forth Chicago indie.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Annual festivals feature various acts, such as Lollapalooza and the Pitchfork Music Festival.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Lollapalooza originated in 1991 as a touring festival, but as of 2005 its home has been Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A 2007 report on the Chicago music industry by the University of Chicago Cultural Policy Center ranked Chicago third among metropolitan U.S. areas in "size of music industry" and fourth among all U.S. cities in "number of concerts and performances".
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has a distinctive fine art tradition.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] For much of the twentieth century, it nurtured a strong style of figurative surrealism, as in the works of Ivan Albright and Ed Paschke.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In 1968 and 1969, members of the Chicago Imagists, such as Roger Brown, Leon Golub, Robert Lostutter, Jim Nutt, and Barbara Rossi produced bizarre representational paintings.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Henry Darger is one of the most celebrated figures of outsider art.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2014, Chicago attracted 50.17 million domestic leisure travelers, 11.09 million domestic business travelers and 1.308 million overseas visitors.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] These visitors contributed more than US$13.7 billion to Chicago's economy.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Upscale shopping along the Magnificent Mile and State Street, thousands of restaurants, as well as Chicago's architecture, continue to draw tourists.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is the United States' third-largest convention destination.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A 2017 study by Walk Score ranked Chicago the sixth-most walkable of fifty largest cities in the United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Most conventions are held at McCormick Place, just south of Soldier Field.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Navy Pier, located just east of Streeterville, is 3,000 ft (910 m) long and houses retail stores, restaurants, museums, exhibition halls and auditoriums.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Ferris wheel first appeared at the World's Columbian Exposition, held in Chicago in 1893.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Willis Tower, formerly named Sears Tower, is a popular destination for tourists.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Among the city's museums are the Adler Planetarium & Astronomy Museum, the Field Museum of Natural History, and the Shedd Aquarium.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Museum Campus joins the southern section of Grant Park, which includes the renowned Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Buckingham Fountain anchors the downtown park along the lakefront.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The University of Chicago's Institute for the Study of Ancient Cultures, West Asia & North Africa has an extensive collection of ancient Egyptian and Near Eastern archaeological artifacts.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago lays claim to a large number of regional specialties that reflect the city's ethnic and working-class roots.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Included among these are its nationally renowned deep-dish pizza; this style is said to have originated at Pizzeria Uno.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago-style thin crust is also popular in the city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Certain Chicago pizza favorites include Lou Malnati's and Giordano's.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago-style hot dog, typically an all-beef hot dog, is loaded with an array of toppings that often includes pickle relish, yellow mustard, pickled sport peppers, tomato wedges, dill pickle spear and topped off with celery salt on a poppy seed bun.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Enthusiasts of the Chicago-style hot dog frown upon the use of ketchup as a garnish, but may prefer to add giardiniera.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A distinctly Chicago sandwich, the Italian beef sandwich is thinly sliced beef simmered in au jus and served on an Italian roll with sweet peppers or spicy giardiniera.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A popular modification is the Combo—an Italian beef sandwich with the addition of an Italian sausage.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Maxwell Street Polish is a grilled or deep-fried kielbasa—on a hot dog roll, topped with grilled onions, yellow mustard, and hot sport peppers.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicken Vesuvio is roasted bone-in chicken cooked in oil and garlic next to garlicky oven-roasted potato wedges and a sprinkling of green peas.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Puerto Rican-influenced jibarito is a sandwich made with flattened, fried green plantains instead of bread.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The mother-in-law is a tamale topped with chili and served on a hot dog bun.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The tradition of serving the Greek dish saganaki while aflame has its origins in Chicago's Greek community.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The appetizer, which consists of a square of fried cheese, is doused with Metaxa and flambéed table-side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago-style barbecue features hardwood smoked rib tips and hot links which were traditionally cooked in an aquarium smoker, a Chicago invention.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Annual festivals feature various Chicago signature dishes, such as Taste of Chicago and the Chicago Food Truck Festival.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] One of the world's most decorated restaurants and a recipient of three Michelin stars, Alinea is located in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Well-known chefs who have had restaurants in Chicago include: Charlie Trotter, Rick Tramonto, Grant Achatz, and Rick Bayless.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2003, *Robb Report* named Chicago the country's "most exceptional dining destination".
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago literature finds its roots in the city's tradition of lucid, direct journalism, lending to a strong tradition of social realism.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Narrative fiction of that time, much of it in the style of "high-flown romance" and "genteel realism", needed a new approach to describe the urban social, political, and economic conditions of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Nonetheless, Chicagoans worked hard to create a literary tradition that would stand the test of time, and create a "city of feeling" out of concrete, steel, vast lake, and open prairie.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Much notable Chicago fiction focuses on the city itself, with social criticism keeping exultation in check.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] At least three short periods in the history of Chicago have had a lasting influence on American literature.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] These include from the time of the Great Chicago Fire to about 1900, what became known as the Chicago Literary Renaissance in the 1910s and early 1920s, and the period of the Great Depression to the 1940s.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] What would become the influential *Poetry* magazine was founded in 1912 by Harriet Monroe, who was working as an art critic for the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The magazine discovered such poets as Gwendolyn Brooks, James Merrill, and John Ashbery.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Eliot's first professionally published poem, "The Love Song of J.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Alfred Prufrock", was first published by *Poetry*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Contributors have included Ezra Pound, William Butler Yeats, William Carlos Williams, Langston Hughes, and Carl Sandburg, among others.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The magazine was instrumental in launching the Imagist and Objectivist poetic movements.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, American poetry continued to evolve in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In the 1980s, a modern form of poetry performance began in Chicago, the poetry slam.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has two Major League Baseball (MLB) teams: the Chicago Cubs of the National League play in Wrigley Field on the North Side; and the Chicago White Sox of the American League play in Rate Field on the South Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The two teams have faced each other in a World Series only once, in 1906.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Cubs are the oldest Major League Baseball team to have never changed their city; they have played in Chicago since 1871.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] They had the dubious honor of having the longest championship drought in American professional sports, failing to win a World Series between 1908 and 2016.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The White Sox have played on the South Side continuously since 1901.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] They have won three World Series titles (1906, 1917, 2005) and six American League pennants, including the first in 1901.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Bears, one of the last two remaining charter members of the National Football League (NFL), have won nine NFL Championships, including the 1985 Super Bowl XX.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Bears play their home games at Soldier Field.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Bulls of the National Basketball Association (NBA) is one of the most recognized basketball teams in the world.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] During the 1990s, with Michael Jordan leading them, the Bulls won six NBA championships in eight seasons.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Blackhawks of the National Hockey League (NHL) began play in 1926, and are one of the "Original Six" teams of the NHL.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Blackhawks have won six Stanley Cups, including in 2010, 2013, and 2015.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Both the Bulls and the Blackhawks play at the United Center.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago Fire FC is a member of Major League Soccer (MLS) and plays at Soldier Field.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Fire have won one league title and four U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Open Cups, since their founding in 1997.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In 1994, the United States hosted a successful FIFA World Cup with games played at Soldier Field.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Stars FC are a team in the National Women's Soccer League (NWSL).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] They previously played in Women's Professional Soccer (WPS), of which they were a founding member, before joining the NWSL in 2013.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] They play at SeatGeek Stadium in Bridgeview, Illinois.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Sky is a professional basketball team playing in the Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] They play home games at the Wintrust Arena.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The team was founded before the 2006 WNBA season began.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Marathon has been held each year since 1977 except for 1987, when a half marathon was run in its place.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Marathon is one of six World Marathon Majors.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Street Course in downtown Chicago had races in the Cup Series and Xfinity Series from 2023 to 2025, while the often forgotten Chicago Motor Speedway held CART and NASCAR Truck Series races.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has also entered into esports with the creation of the OpTic Chicago, a professional Call of Duty team that participates within the CDL.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] When Chicago was incorporated in 1837, it chose the motto *Urbs in Horto*, a Latin phrase which means "City in a Garden".
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Today, the Chicago Park District consists of more than 570 parks with over 8,000 acres (3,200 ha) of municipal parkland.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] There are 31 sand beaches, a plethora of museums, two world-class conservatories, and 50 nature areas.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Lincoln Park, the largest of the city's parks, covers 1,200 acres (490 ha) and has over 20 million visitors each year, making it third in the number of visitors after Central Park in New York City, and the National Mall and Memorial Parks in Washington, D.C.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] There is a historic boulevard system, a network of wide, tree-lined boulevards which connect a number of Chicago parks.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The boulevards and the parks were authorized by the Illinois legislature in 1869.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A number of Chicago neighborhoods emerged along these roadways in the 19th century.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The building of the boulevard system continued intermittently until 1942.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] It includes nineteen boulevards, eight parks, and six squares, along twenty-six miles of interconnected streets.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The *Chicago Park Boulevard System Historic District* was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2018.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] With berths for more than 6,000 boats, the Chicago Park District operates the nation's largest municipal harbor system.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Washington Park is also one of the city's biggest parks; covering nearly 400 acres (160 ha).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The park is listed on the National Register of Historic Places listings in South Side Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The government of the City of Chicago is divided into executive and legislative branches.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The mayor of Chicago is the chief executive, elected by general election for a term of four years, with no term limits.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The mayor appoints commissioners and other officials who oversee the various departments.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] As well as the mayor, Chicago's clerk and treasurer are also elected citywide.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The City Council is the legislative branch and is made up of 50 alderpersons, one elected from each ward in the city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The council takes official action through the passage of ordinances and resolutions and approves the city budget.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Police Department provides law enforcement and the Chicago Fire Department provides fire suppression and emergency medical services for the city and its residents.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Civil and criminal law cases are heard in the Cook County Circuit Court of the State of Illinois court system, or in the Northern District of Illinois, in the federal system.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In the state court, the public prosecutor is the Illinois state's attorney; in the Federal court it is the United States attorney.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] During much of the last half of the 19th century, Chicago's politics were dominated by a growing Democratic Party organization.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] During the 1880s and 1890s, Chicago had a powerful radical tradition with large and highly organized socialist, anarchist and labor organizations.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] For much of the 20th century, Chicago has been among the largest and most reliable Democratic strongholds in the United States; with Chicago's Democratic vote the state of Illinois has been "solid blue" in presidential elections since 1992.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Even before then, it was not unheard of for Republican presidential candidates to win handily in downstate Illinois, only to lose statewide due to large Democratic margins in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The citizens of Chicago have not elected a Republican mayor since 1927, when William Thompson was voted into office.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The strength of the party in Chicago is partly a consequence of Illinois state politics, where the Republicans have come to represent rural and farm concerns while the Democrats support urban issues such as Chicago's public school funding.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago contains less than 25% of the state's population, but it is split between eight of Illinois' 17 districts in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] All eight of the city's representatives are Democrats; only two Republicans have represented a significant portion of the city since 1973, for one term each: Robert P.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Hanrahan from 1973 to 1975, and Michael Patrick Flanagan from 1995 to 1997.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Machine politics persisted in Chicago after the decline of similar machines in other large U.S. cities.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] During much of that time, the city administration found opposition mainly from a liberal "independent" faction of the Democratic Party.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The independents finally gained control of city government in 1983 with the election of Harold Washington (in office 1983–1987).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] From 1989 until May 16, 2011, Chicago was under the leadership of its longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Because of the dominance of the Democratic Party in Chicago, the Democratic primary vote held in the spring is generally more significant than the general elections in November for U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The aldermanic, mayoral, and other city offices are filled through nonpartisan elections with runoffs as needed.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is home of former United States President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama; Barack Obama was formerly a state legislator representing Chicago and later a U.S. senator.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Obamas' residence is located near the University of Chicago in Kenwood on the city's south side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago experienced major rises in violent crime in the 1920s, in the late 1960s, and in the 2020s.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's biggest criminal justice challenges have changed little over the last 50 years, and statistically reside with homicide, armed robbery, gang violence, and aggravated battery.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has a higher murder rate than the larger cities of New York and Los Angeles.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] However, while it has a large absolute number of crimes due to its size, Chicago is not among the top-25 most violent cities in the United States.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Murder rates in Chicago vary greatly depending on the neighborhood in question.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The neighborhoods of Englewood on the South Side, and Austin on the West side, for example, have homicide rates that are ten times higher than other parts of the city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has an estimated population of over 100,000 active gang members from nearly 60 factions.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] According to reports in 2013, "most of Chicago's violent crime comes from gangs trying to maintain control of drug-selling territories," and is specifically related to the activities of the Sinaloa Cartel, which is active in several American cities.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Violent crime rates vary significantly by area of the city, with more economically developed areas having low rates, but other sections have much higher rates of crime.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2013, the violent crime rate was 910 per 100,000 people; the murder rate was 10.4 per 100,000 – while high crime districts saw 38.9 murders, low crime districts saw 2.5 murders per 100,000.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's long history of public corruption regularly draws the attention of federal law enforcement and federal prosecutors.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] From 2012 to 2019, 33 Chicago alderpersons were convicted on corruption charges, roughly one third of those elected in the time period.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A report from the Office of the Legislative Inspector General noted that over half of Chicago's elected alderpersons took illegal campaign contributions in 2013.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Most corruption cases in Chicago are prosecuted by the U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Attorney's office, as legal jurisdiction makes most offenses punishable as a federal crime.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago Public Schools (CPS) is the governing body of the school district that contains over 600 public elementary and high schools citywide, including several selective-admission magnet schools.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] There are eleven selective enrollment high schools in the Chicago Public Schools, designed to meet the needs of Chicago's most academically advanced students.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] These schools offer a rigorous curriculum with mainly honors and Advanced Placement (AP) courses.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Walter Payton College Prep High School is ranked number one in the city of Chicago and the state of Illinois.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago high school rankings are determined by the average test scores on state achievement tests.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The district, with an enrollment exceeding 400,545 students (2013–2014 20th Day Enrollment), is the third-largest in the U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] In September 2012, teachers for the Chicago Teachers Union went on strike for the first time since 1987 over pay, resources, and other issues.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] According to 2014 data, Chicago's "choice system", where students who test or apply and may attend one of approximately 130 public high schools, sorts students of different achievement levels into different schools (high performing, middle performing, and low performing schools).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has a network of Lutheran schools, and several private schools are run by other denominations and faiths, such as the Ida Crown Jewish Academy in West Ridge.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago operates Catholic schools, including Jesuit preparatory schools and others.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] A number of private schools are completely secular.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] There is also the private Chicago Academy for the Arts, a high school focused on six different artistic disciplines, and the public Chicago High School for the Arts, a high school focused on five disciplines (visual arts, theatre, musical theatre, dance, and music).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Public Library system operates three regional libraries and 77 neighborhood branches, including the central library.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Since the 1850s, Chicago has been a world center of higher education and research with several universities.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] These institutions consistently rank among the top "National Universities" in the United States, as determined by *U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Highly regarded universities in Chicago and the surrounding area are the University of Chicago; Northwestern University; Illinois Institute of Technology; Loyola University Chicago; DePaul University; Columbia College Chicago and the University of Illinois Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] William Rainey Harper, the first president of the University of Chicago, was instrumental in the creation of the junior college concept, establishing nearby Joliet Junior College as the first in the nation in 1901.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] His legacy continues with the multiple community colleges in the Chicago proper, including the seven City Colleges of Chicago: Richard J.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Daley College, Kennedy–King College, Malcolm X College, Olive–Harvey College, Truman College, Harold Washington College, and Wilbur Wright College, in addition to the privately held MacCormac College.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area is a major media hub and the third-largest media market in the United States, after New York City and Los Angeles.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Each of the big five U.S. television networks, NBC, ABC, CBS, Fox and The CW, directly owns and operates a high-definition television station in Chicago (WMAQ 5, WLS 7, WBBM 2, WFLD 32 and WGN-TV 9, respectively).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] WGN is owned by the CW through a majority stake held in the network by the Nexstar Media Group, which acquired it from its founding owner Tribune Broadcasting in 2019.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] WGN was once carried, with some programming differences, as "WGN America" on cable and satellite TV nationwide and in parts of the Caribbean.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] WGN America eventually became NewsNation in 2021.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has been the home of several prominent talk shows, including *The Oprah Winfrey Show*, *Steve Harvey Show*, *The Rosie Show*, *The Jerry Springer Show*, *The Phil Donahue Show*, *The Jenny Jones Show*, and more.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has one PBS member station (its second: WYCC 20, removed its affiliation with PBS in 2017): WTTW 11, producer of shows such as *Sneak Previews*, *The Frugal Gourmet*, *Lamb Chop's Play-Along* and *The McLaughlin Group*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] As of 2018, *Windy City Live* is Chicago's only daytime talk show, which is hosted by Val Warner and Ryan Chiaverini at ABC7 Studios with a live weekday audience.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Since 1999, *Judge Mathis* also films his syndicated arbitration-based reality court show at the NBC Tower.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Beginning in January 2019, *Newsy* began producing 12 of its 14 hours of live news programming per day from its new facility in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Most of Chicago's television stations are owned and operated by the big television network companies.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Two major daily newspapers are published in Chicago: the *Chicago Tribune* and the *Chicago Sun-Times*, with the Tribune having the larger circulation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] The entertainment and cultural magazine *Time Out Chicago* and *GRAB* magazine are published in the city, as well as local music magazine *Chicago Innerview*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is the home of satirical national news outlet, *The Onion*, and its sister pop-culture publication, *The A.V.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has five 50,000 watt AM radio stations: the Audacy-owned WBBM and WSCR; the Tribune Broadcasting-owned WGN; the Cumulus Media-owned WLS; and the ESPN Radio-owned WMVP.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is also home to a number of national radio shows, including *Beyond the Beltway* with Bruce DuMont on Sunday evenings.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p02] WBEZ produces nationally aired programs such as PRI's *This American Life* and NPR's *Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!*.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is a major transportation hub in the United States and North America.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] It is an important component in global distribution, as it is the third-largest inter-modal port in the world after Hong Kong and Singapore.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The city of Chicago has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In 2015, 26.5 percent of Chicago households were without a car, and increased slightly to 27.5 percent in 2016.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago averaged 1.12 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Due to Chicago's wheel tax, residents of Chicago who own a vehicle are required to purchase a Chicago City Vehicle Sticker.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In established Residential Parking Zones, only local residents can purchase Zone-specific parking stickers for themselves and guests.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago since 2009 has relinquished rights to its public street parking.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In 2008, as Chicago struggled to close a growing budget deficit, the city agreed to a 75-year, $1.16 billion deal to lease its parking meter system to an operating company created by Morgan Stanley, called Chicago Parking Meters LLC.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The rights of the parking ticket lease end in 2081, and since 2022 have already recouped over $1.5 billion in revenue for Chicago Parking Meters LLC investors.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Eight mainline and four auxiliary interstate highways (41 (mostly in Wisconsin), 55, 57, 65 (only in Indiana), 80 (also in Indiana), 88, 90 (also in Indiana), 94 (also in Indiana), 190, 290, 294, and 355) run through Chicago and its suburbs.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] I-490 is currently under construction on the west side of O'Hare Airport.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Segments that link to the city center are named after influential politicians, with three of them named after former U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Presidents (Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Reagan) and one named after two-time Democratic candidate Adlai Stevenson.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Kennedy and Dan Ryan Expressways are the busiest state maintained routes in the entire state of Illinois.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Regional Transportation Authority (RTA) coordinates the operation of the three service boards: CTA, Metra, and Pace.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Beginning in June 2026, the RTA will be replaced by the Northern Illinois Transit Authority (NITA).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Northern Indiana Commuter Transportation District (NICTD) operates the South Shore Line, which provides commuter rail service from Millennium Station to Northwest Indiana.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Since March 2026, it consists of two services: the Lakeshore Corridor to South Bend and the Monon Corridor to Munster/Dyer.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Greyhound Lines provides inter-city bus service to and from the city at the Chicago Bus Station, and Chicago is also the hub for the Midwest network of Megabus.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Amtrak long distance and inter-city rail services originate from Chicago Union Station.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is one of the largest hubs of passenger rail service in the nation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The services terminate in Port Huron, St.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Paul, the San Francisco Area, New York City, New Orleans, Portland, Oregon, Seattle, Miami, Milwaukee, Carbondale, Quincy, Boston, St.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Louis, Kansas City, Grand Rapids, Los Angeles, San Antonio, and Pontiac, Michigan.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Future service will terminate at Moline.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago has a total of four active rail terminals: Chicago Union Station, Ogilvie Transportation Center, LaSalle Street Station, and Millennium Station.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Amtrak only serves Union Station, while Metra serves all four stations.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The South Shore Line services uses Millennium Station as its Chicago terminal.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In July 2013, the bicycle-sharing system Divvy was launched with 750 bikes and 75 docking stations.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] It is operated by Lyft for the Chicago Department of Transportation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] As of July 2019, Divvy operated 5800 bicycles at 608 stations, covering almost all of the city, excluding Pullman, Rosedale, Beverly, Belmont Cragin and Edison Park.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In May 2019, The City of Chicago announced its Chicago's Electric Shared Scooter Pilot Program, scheduled to run from June 15 to October 15.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The program started on June 15 with 10 different scooter companies, including scooter sharing market leaders Bird, Jump, Lime and Lyft.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Each company was allowed to bring 250 electric scooters, although both Bird and Lime claimed that they experienced a higher demand for their scooters.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The program ended on October 15, with nearly 800,000 rides taken.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is the largest hub in the railroad industry.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] All five Class I railroads meet in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] As of 2002, severe freight train congestion caused trains to take as long to get through the Chicago region as it took to get there from the West Coast of the country (about 2 days).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Department of Transportation, the volume of imported and exported goods transported via rail to, from, or through Chicago is forecast to increase nearly 150 percent between 2010 and 2040.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] CREATE, the Chicago Region Environmental and Transportation Efficiency Program, comprises about 70 programs, including crossovers, overpasses and underpasses, that intend to significantly improve the speed of freight movements in the Chicago area.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is served by O'Hare International Airport, the world's busiest airport measured by airline operations, on the far Northwest Side, and Midway International Airport on the Southwest Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In 2005, O'Hare was the world's busiest airport by aircraft movements and the second-busiest by total passenger traffic.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] O'Hare is major hub for American Airlines and United Airlines.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Midway is a major operating base for Southwest Airlines.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Both O'Hare and Midway are owned and operated by the City of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The CTA's Blue Line provides direct rail access to O'Hare, while the Orange Line provides direct rail access to Midway.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Gary/Chicago International Airport and Chicago Rockford International Airport, located in Gary, Indiana and Rockford, Illinois, respectively, can serve as alternative Chicago area airports, however they do not offer as many commercial flights as O'Hare and Midway.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In recent years the state of Illinois has been leaning towards building an entirely new airport in the Illinois suburbs of Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The City of Chicago is the world headquarters for United Airlines, the world's third-largest airline.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Port of Chicago consists of several major port facilities within the city of Chicago operated by the Illinois International Port District (formerly known as the Chicago Regional Port District).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The central element of the Port District, Calumet Harbor, is maintained by the U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Electricity for most of northern Illinois is provided by Commonwealth Edison, also known as ComEd.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Their service territory borders Iroquois County to the south, the Wisconsin border to the north, the Iowa border to the west and the Indiana border to the east.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In northern Illinois, ComEd (a division of Exelon) operates the greatest number of nuclear generating plants in any U.S. state.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Because of this, ComEd reports indicate that Chicago receives about 75% of its electricity from nuclear power.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Recently, the city began installing wind turbines on government buildings to promote renewable energy.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Natural gas is provided by Peoples Gas, a subsidiary of Integrys Energy Group, which is headquartered in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Domestic and industrial waste was once incinerated but it is now landfilled, mainly in the Calumet area.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] From 1995 to 2008, the city had a blue bag program to divert recyclable refuse from landfills.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Because of low participation in the blue bag programs, the city began a pilot program for blue bin recycling like other cities.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] This proved successful and blue bins were rolled out across the city.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Illinois Medical District is on the Near West Side.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] It includes Rush University Medical Center, ranked as the second best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] News & World Report* for 2014–16, the University of Illinois Medical Center at Chicago, Jesse Brown VA Hospital, and John H.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Hospital of Cook County, one of the busiest trauma centers in the nation.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] Two of the country's premier academic medical centers, Northwestern Memorial Hospital and the University of Chicago Medical Center, reside in Chicago.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Chicago campus of Northwestern University includes the Feinberg School of Medicine; Northwestern Memorial Hospital, which was ranked as the best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] News & World Report* for 2017–18; the Shirley Ryan AbilityLab (formerly named the Rehabilitation Institute of Chicago), which was ranked the best U.S. rehabilitation hospital by *U.S.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] News & World Report*; the new Prentice Women's Hospital; and Ann & Robert H.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The University of Illinois College of Medicine at UIC is the second-largest medical school in the United States (2,600 students, including those at campuses in Peoria, Rockford and Urbana–Champaign).
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] In addition, the Chicago Medical School and Loyola University Chicago's Stritch School of Medicine are located in the suburbs of North Chicago and Maywood, respectively.
[src:cornhole/chicago-illinois-p03] The Midwestern University Chicago College of Osteopathic Medicine is in Downers Grove.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The game was first described in Heyliger de Windt's 1883 patent for "Parlor Quoits", which displays most of the features of modern cornhole, but uses a square hole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Quoits is a game similar to horseshoes, played by throwing steel rings at a metal spike.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Several earlier "parlor quoits" patents had sought to re-create quoit gameplay in an indoor environment, but De Windt's was the first to use bean bags and a slanted board with a hole as the target.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] He sold the rights to the game to a Massachusetts toy manufacturer which marketed a version of it under the name "Faba Baga".
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Unlike modern cornhole, which has one hole and one size of bags, a Faba Baga board had two different-sized holes, worth different point values, and provided each player with one extra-large bag per round, which could score double points.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In September 1974, *Popular Mechanics* magazine published an article written by Carolyn Farrell about a similar game called "bean-bag bull's-eye".
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Bean-bag bull's-eye was played on a board the same width as modern cornhole boards (24 in [60 cm]), but only 36 in [90 cm] long as opposed to the 48 in [120 cm] length used in cornhole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The hole was the same diameter (6 in [15 cm]) but was centered 8 in [20 cm] (rather than 9 in [23 cm]) from the back of the board.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Each player threw two bags, weighing eight ounces (230 g) each, "in succession".
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The boards in bean-bag bull's-eye were placed "about 30 ft . [9 m] apart for adults, 10 ft . [3 m] for kids." Scoring was essentially the same as that used in cornhole (three points for a bag in the hole, one point for a bag remaining on the board) and also used cancellation scoring.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In the Chicago area, a similar game is referred to as "bags" or "bean bags", but uses rectangular bags.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The game spread in Chicago, Illinois, and the Northwest region of Indiana in the late 1970s and early 1980s, perhaps due to the *Popular Mechanics* article mentioned above.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Cornhole as it is now known originated and gained popularity on Cincinnati's west side (near Ferguson Avenue) in the 1980s and spread to surrounding areas in Kentucky and Southeast Indiana.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The American Cornhole Organization (ACO) was established in 2005 by Frank Geers and is headquartered in Milford, Ohio.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The ACO claims on its website to be the "governing body for the sport of cornhole".
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The American Cornhole League (ACL) was founded in 2015 by Stacey Moore.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] According to the ACL's website, it promotes and develops cornhole as a sport on every level, and created software and apps to manage cornhole leagues, tournaments, special events, and player development.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The American Cornhole Association (ACA) is an organization whose sole mission is to help cornhole players enjoy the game of cornhole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The United Kingdom Cornhole League (UKCL) was founded in 2021 by Daniel Lilley.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] It promotes competitive tournaments across the United Kingdom and develops cornhole as a sport.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Cornhole matches are played with two sets of four bags (eight total), two boards and two, four, or eight players.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Each set of bags should be distinguishable from the other, usually by using different colors.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The American Cornhole League's rules call for double-seamed fabric bags measuring 6 by 6 inches (150 by 150 mm) and weighing 15.5 to 16.5 ounces (440 to 470 g).
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Although bags used to be filled with preserved corn kernels (hence "cornhole") or dried beans, the American Cornhole Organization developed bags filled with plastic resin or other materials that will maintain a consistent weight and shape over many throws without deforming.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Bags are usually dual-sided, with each side of the bag being a different material that can affect grip and react faster or slower on the board's surface.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Faster bags are often preferred in humid conditions when bags will not slide as readily.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Additionally, professional players may opt for different materials depending on their personal throwing styles.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Players with a lower, faster throw may use more rotation and prefer a slower bag material, whereas players with higher, slower throws may use less rotation and prefer a more reactive bag.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] As per the American Cornhole Organization Rules, each board is 2 by 4 feet (0.61 by 1.22 m), with a 6-inch-diameter (15 cm) hole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The hole's center is positioned 9 inches (230 mm) down from the center of the top edge of the board.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Each board is angled with the top edge of the playing surface 12 inches (300 mm) above the ground, and the bottom edge 3–4 inches (76–102 mm) above the ground.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A standard court places the two boards 33 feet (10 m) or 27 feet (8.2 m) apart, measuring from the bottom edge of the boards.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Different (usually shorter) distances may be used if space is limited or if younger players are participating.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Some smaller versions of the game, with scaled-down boards, bags, and holes are available specifically for children.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The areas immediately to the left and right of the boards are the pitcher's boxes.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The line (either drawn or imaginary) extending from the bottom edge of the board in both the left and right direction is the foul line.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] When throwing the bags, players cannot step past the foul line or else the throw does not count.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A cornhole match is separated into innings (or frames).
[src:cornhole/cornhole] During each inning, each player or team will throw their designated four bags.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The manner in which the bags are thrown depends on which format of cornhole is being played: singles (1 vs.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] 1), both players throw their four bags while standing on opposite sides of the same board (left vs. right pitcher's box), alternating throws between the two players.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] After all eight bags are thrown, both players walk to the opposite board, while remaining in their lane, to tally the score.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] To begin the next inning, both players turn around to throw at the other board in the same manner.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The effect of this is that by always staying in their respective lane, the two players will alternate each inning throwing from the left vs. right pitcher's box.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] 2), one partner from each team stands in the left pitcher's box of one board while the other partner stands in the right pitcher's box of the opposite board.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Thus, each team's partners are on opposite ends, facing each other, both in the same lane.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In doubles, players may not change sides, i.e. one partner will throw from the left pitcher's box of one board and the other from the right pitcher's box of the other board for the entire game.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] 4), play is identical to doubles, but with two teammates at each of the two boards, one pair in the left pitcher's box of one board and the other pair in the right pitcher's box of the opposite board, each pair facing each other, in the same lane.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Instead of each partner pitching four bags per inning (as in doubles), in crew each teammate pitches two bags per inning, again alternating throws both with the opposing team (as in singles and doubles) and with the player's teammate who is standing with them at the same board.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Note that in doubles and crew, the score for any inning is based on eight throws per team, as opposed to four throws per player in singles.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In all formats, the pitcher must throw the bag within 20 seconds.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The time begins when the pitcher is inside the pitcher's box with an intent to throw.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The first pitch of an inning goes to whichever player or team scored in the previous inning.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] If neither player or team scored in the previous inning, then whichever pitched first in the previous inning will again pitch first in the next inning.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The first pitch of the first inning can be decided by a coin toss.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A legal pitch must be tossed while the pitcher's feet are within the pitcher's box.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] If the pitcher begins the throw with a foot beyond the foul line or otherwise steps beyond the foul line before releasing the bag, the pitch is a foul and does not count.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A foul throw cannot be re-taken and the bag is removed from play before continuing.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] If a foul bag moves other bags in the field of play, those bags are returned to their prior position before continuing, including if a bag was moved into the hole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] If a bag lands only partially on the board and is also touching the ground, it does not count and is removed before continuing.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] To score points, bags must be on the surface of the board or fall through the hole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] To score three points, a bag may fall directly into the hole, slide into the hole after hitting the board, or be knocked into the hole by another bag.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A bag remaining on the board scores one point.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A bag partially on the board and partially on the ground ("dirt bag") does not count and should be removed before the next throw.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In cornhole, cancellation scoring is used.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] When the scores are tallied at the end of an inning, whichever player or team scores higher is awarded points equal to the difference between both sides.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] For example, if Team A scores 12 points in an inning and Team B scores 10 points, then Team A is awarded two points (12 minus 10); whereas if Team A and Team B both score 12 points, the difference is zero, and no one scores.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Play continues until one player or team reaches or exceeds 21 points at the end of an inning.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] By using cancellation scoring, it is only possible for one side (or neither side) to score in any inning, so match ties are impossible.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Different variations in scoring or house rules are sometimes used.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Sometimes, a bag hanging over the hole, but which has not fallen through, is scored as two points.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Other variations (such as British rules) include requiring one team to reach exactly 21 points without going over to win.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] If a team exceeds 21 points after an inning (called "busting"), different punishments might be used such as automatically returning to 15 points, returning to the team's prior score, returning to the prior score minus one, etc.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In some versions, if a team "busts" three times, their opponents automatically win the match.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Gameplay strategy varies by player and skill level.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] At the professional level, players can easily slide all four bags into the hole if no bag blocks the path.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Defensive strategies are often employed to slow down gameplay or force opponents to make difficult decisions.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Bags can be made out of different materials to help strategies such as the blocker bag be easier to execute.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] There are many types of shots that players use depending on the situation.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The slide shot is one of the most basic shots and is when a bag lands on the bottom two thirds of the board and slides into the hole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Another shot used is the blocker bag as mentioned above along with an airmail.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] A more complicated shot is the bully bag where a player will push their opponent's bag away from the hole either to the left or right, while keeping their own bag in line with the hole making it difficult for the opponent to get their bag into the hole.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The rolling shot is another technique that allows the player to "rollover" any bags blocking the hole such as a blocker, although this shot is more complicated.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Practicing and perfecting these shots allows players to be prepared and ready for any strategies their opponents throw at them.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Knowing when to utilize each shot is an important part of the game and can help aid players of all skill levels.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The American Cornhole Organization ranks amateur and professional cornhole players through their World Rankings.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Players are world ranked by division, including Singles, Doubles, Women, Seniors and Juniors.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The American Cornhole League ranks their players based on points earned through local and regional tournaments.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The points earned per tournament are based on the level of play.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] These levels include open, advanced, competitive, intermediate and novice with open providing the most points based on placement.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Points are also used to determine the pros of the ACL.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] Since 2023, the World Cornhole Organization (WCO) has organised an annual international tournament, the WCO World Cup, to crown a world champion national team.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] As of 2025 the 2025 World Cup in Poreč featured 26 countries from four continents, making it the largest Cornhole World Cup in history.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] In the 2025 final, Team USA won the title after a dramatic match against Slovenia.
[src:cornhole/cornhole] The establishment of the WCO and its World Cup marks a shift of Cornhole from a regional pastime — especially in North America — toward a structured, global competition with standardized rules and growing international participation.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The sport was codified in England in the 1860s and then spread overseas.
[src:cornhole/croquet] However, similar games have been recorded back to the late Middle Ages.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Today, there are several variations of the game.
[src:cornhole/croquet] At its highest level, the game is played internationally with top players coming from Australia, Egypt, England, South Africa, Spain, and the United States among other countries.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The sport can be played equally well by men and women.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In 2018, two international championships open to both sexes were won by women.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In all forms of croquet, individual players or teams take turns striking the balls, scoring points by knocking them through a hoop.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The game ends when a player or team reaches a predetermined number of points.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Several variations exist that differ in when and how a stroke may be legally played, when points are scored, the layout of the lawn, and the target score.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Commonly, social games adopt further non-standard variations to adapt play to the conditions.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In all versions, players of all ages and genders compete on equal terms and are ranked together.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Two versions of the game are directly governed by the World Croquet Federation, which organises individual and team World Championships.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Other regional variants which developed in parallel remain common in parts of the world.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Association croquet is played between two individuals or teams, each playing with two balls.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The object of the game is to be the first to strike each of one's balls through all six hoops in both directions, in a fixed order, and to strike the central peg.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Each of these actions scores a point, with the maximum score being 26 points.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The first four turns must be taken to play the four balls onto the lawn from one of two "baulk lines" defined as one yard into the lawn on the western half of the south boundary and the eastern half of the north boundary.
[src:cornhole/croquet] After this, a player elects at the start of each turn which of their two balls to play for the duration of that turn.
[src:cornhole/croquet] During a turn, a player may earn extra shots in two ways.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A player earns a single extra shot by scoring a hoop point (hitting the striker's ball through a hoop), or two extra shots by causing their ball to contact another ball-an action called a "roquet".
[src:cornhole/croquet] When a roquet is made, the player may pick up their ball and place it in contact with the roqueted ball.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The next shot must move both the player's ball and the roqueted ball, and it is the "croquet" stroke that gives the game its name.
[src:cornhole/croquet] After a successful croquet stroke, the player has a single further shot, known as the "continuation".
[src:cornhole/croquet] During a turn, each of the other three balls may only be croqueted once between hoop points, but by stringing together a series of roquets, croquets, and scored hoops, several points may be scored in a single turn.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Advanced variants of association croquet give further penalties to dissuade skilled players from running every hoop with a ball on a single *break*, while handicap versions give weaker players chances to continue play after making an error.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The extra turns, called "bisques" are effective in levelling the odds of winning.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Golf croquet is played between two individuals or teams, each playing with two balls.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The object of the game is to reach a certain number of points, typically seven, earned by being the first to run a hoop.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The game opens by playing each ball into the lawn from the fourth (south-eastern) corner of the lawn.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Balls must be played in order (for the primary ball colours, this is blue, red, black, and yellow), and this order of play is maintained throughout the game.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Hoops are contested in a fixed order, with a point awarded to the owner of the first ball to pass through the hoop in the correct direction.
[src:cornhole/croquet] After a point is awarded, all players move on to contest the next hoop.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Balls that are played more than halfway to the next hoop before a point is scored are considered offside, and are moved to penalty areas.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Golf croquet is the fastest-growing version of the game, owing largely to its simplicity and competitiveness.
[src:cornhole/croquet] There is an especially large interest in competitive success among players in Egypt.
[src:cornhole/croquet] By comparison with association croquet, golf croquet requires a smaller variety of shots and emphasises strategic skills and accurate shot-making.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Games are shorter, balls are more likely to be hit harder, and 'jump' shots are more likely to be witnessed, where a ball is played to deliberately jump off the ground and over another ball.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The American-rules version of croquet is the dominant version of the game in the United States and is also widely played in Canada.
[src:cornhole/croquet] It is governed by the United States Croquet Association.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Its genesis is mostly in association croquet, but it differs in a number of important ways that reflect the home-grown traditions of American "backyard" croquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Official rules were first published in 1894 by the Spalding Athletic Library, as adopted by the National American Croquet Association.
[src:cornhole/croquet] American six-wicket uses the same six-wicket layout as both association croquet and golf croquet, and is also played by two individuals or teams, each owning two balls.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Like association croquet, the object of the game is to be the first to pass each of their balls through all six hoops in both directions and to strike the central peg, for a total of 26 points.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Unlike association croquet, balls are always played in the same sequence (blue, red, black, yellow).
[src:cornhole/croquet] The limitation of roqueting each ball once between hoop points is, unlike in association croquet, carried over from turn to turn until the ball scores the next hoop.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In American six-wicket, this is termed "deadness", and a separate board is required to keep track of the deadness for all four balls.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A further difference is the more restrictive boundary-line rules of American croquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In the American game, roqueting a ball out of bounds or running a hoop so that the ball goes out of bounds causes the turn to end, and balls that go out of bounds are replaced only nine inches (23 cm) from the boundary rather than one yard (91 cm) as in association croquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] "Attacking" balls on the boundary line to bring them into play is thus far more challenging.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Nine-wicket croquet is played mainly in the United States and Canada.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In this version of croquet, there are nine wickets, two stakes, and up to six players with one ball each.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The course is arranged in a double-diamond pattern, with one stake at each end of the course.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Players start at one stake, navigate one side of the double diamond, hit the turning stake, then navigate the opposite side of the double diamond and hit the starting stake to end.
[src:cornhole/croquet] If playing individually (*Cutthroat*), the first player to stake out is the winner.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In partnership play, all members of a team must stake out, and a player might choose to avoid staking out (becoming a *Rover*) in order to help a lagging teammate.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Each time a ball is roqueted, the striker gets two bonus shots.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The second bonus shot ("continuation shot") is an ordinary shot played from where the striker ball came to rest.
[src:cornhole/croquet] An alternative endgame is "poison": in this variant, a player who has scored the last wicket but not hit the starting stake becomes a "poison ball", which may eliminate other balls from the game by roqueting them.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A non-poison ball that roquets a poison ball has the normal options.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A poison ball that hits a stake or passes through any wicket (possibly through the action of a non-poison player) is eliminated.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The last person remaining is the winner.
[src:cornhole/croquet] International croquet competition is governed by the World Croquet Federation, often referred to as the WCF.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet Europe is a subsidiary of the WCF set up to manage European croquet tournaments and provide a closer link to European Clubs in the management of international croquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] As well as club-level games, county-level tournaments, and leagues, there are regular world championships and international matches between croquet-playing countries.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The sport has particularly strong followings in the UK, Spain, US, New Zealand, Australia, and Egypt; many other countries also play.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Every four years, the top countries play in the World Team Championships in AC (the MacRobertson Shield) and GC (the Openshaw Shield).
[src:cornhole/croquet] The current world rankings show England in top place for AC, followed by Australia in second place, and New Zealand in third place, with the United States in fourth position.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The same four countries appear in the top six of the GC country rankings, below Egypt in top position, and with Spain at number six.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Individual World Championships usually take place every two or three years.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The 2025 AC World Championships took place in West Palm Beach, Florida; the winner was Reg Bamford.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The current Women's Association Croquet World Champion (2023) is Debbie Lines of England.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The most prestigious international team competition in association croquet is the MacRobertson International Croquet Shield.
[src:cornhole/croquet] It is contested every three to four years among Australia, England, New Zealand, and the United States.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Other nations compete in Tier 2 and Tier 3 World Team Championships.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Teams are promoted and relegated between the lower tiers, but there is no relegation to or promotion from the MacRobertson Shield.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The current holders of the MacRobertson Shield are England, who won the title in 2023.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The next MacRobertson International Croquet Shield competition will take place in London in July/August 2025.
[src:cornhole/croquet] At the Golf Croquet World Team Championships, eight nations contest the Openshaw Shield.
[src:cornhole/croquet] There is promotion and relegation between Tier 1, Tier 2, and Tier 3.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The current holders of the Openshaw Shield are the USA, who won in 2025.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In April 2013, Reg Bamford of South Africa beat Ahmed Nasr of Egypt in the final of the Golf Croquet World Championship in Cairo, becoming the first person to simultaneously hold the title in both association croquet and golf croquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] As of 2025, the Golf Croquet World Champion was Blake Fields (USA), and the Women's Golf Croquet World Champion was Jamie Gumbrell (Australia).
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet was an event at the 1900 Summer Olympics.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Roque, an American variation on croquet, was an event at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet is recognized as the first Olympic sport to include female participants.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In the 1900 Olympic croquet events, France claimed victory in all three competitions.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Gaston Aumoitte won the one-ball singles, Chrétien Waydelich won the two-ball singles, and the doubles event was won by the pair of Gaston Aumoitte and Georges Johin, securing all the medals as all 10 participants were French.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The oldest document to bear the word *croquet* with a description of the modern game is the set of rules registered by Isaac Spratt in November 1856 with the Stationers' Company of London.
[src:cornhole/croquet] This record is now in the Public Record Office.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In 1868, the first croquet all-comers meet was held at Moreton-in-Marsh, Gloucestershire, and in the same year, the All England Croquet Club was formed in Wimbledon, London.
[src:cornhole/croquet] By the 12th century, a team ball game called **la soule** or **choule**, akin to a chaotic version of hockey or football (depending on whether sticks were used), was regularly played in France and southern Britain between villages or parishes; it was attested in Cornwall as early as 1283.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In the book *Queen of Games: The History of Croquet*, Nicky Smith presents two theories of the origin of the modern game of croquet, which took England by storm in the 1860s and then spread overseas.
[src:cornhole/croquet] This was the explanation given in the ninth edition of *Encyclopædia Britannica*, dated 1877.
[src:cornhole/croquet] While the name *pall-mall* and various games bearing this name also appeared elsewhere (France and Italy), the description above suggests that the croquet-like games in particular were popular in England by the early 17th century.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Some other early modern sources refer to pall-mall being played over a large distance (as in golf); however, an image in Strutt's 1801 book shows a croquet-like ground billiards game (balls on the ground, hoop, bats, and peg) being played over a *short*, garden-sized distance.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The image's caption describes the game as "a curious ancient pastime", confirming that croquet games were not new in early-19th-century England.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In Samuel Johnson's 1755 dictionary, his definition of "pall-mall" clearly describes a game with similarities to modern croquet: "A play in which the ball is struck with a mallet through an iron ring".
[src:cornhole/croquet] However, there is no evidence that pall-mall involved the croquet stroke, which is the distinguishing characteristic of the modern game.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The second theory is that the rules of the modern game of croquet arrived in Ireland during the 1850s, perhaps after being brought there from Brittany, where a similar game was played on the beaches.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Regular contact between Ireland and France had continued since the Norman invasion of Ireland in 1169.
[src:cornhole/croquet] By no later than the early 15th century, the game **jeu de mail** (itself ancestral to pall-mall and perhaps to indoor billiards) was popular in France, including in the courts of Henry II in the 16th century and Louis XIV of the 17th.
[src:cornhole/croquet] At least one version of it, **rouët** ('wheel'), was a multi-ball lawn game.
[src:cornhole/croquet] There is, however, no pre-1858 Irish document that describes the way the game was played; in particular, there is no reference to the distinctive croquet stroke, which is described above under "Variations: Association".
[src:cornhole/croquet] John Jaques apparently claimed in a letter to Arthur Lillie in 1873 that he had himself seen the game played in Ireland, writing, "I made the implements and published directions (such as they were) before Mr.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Spratt [mentioned above] introduced the subject to me." Whatever the truth of the matter, Jaques certainly played an important role in popularising the game, producing editions of the rules in 1857, 1860, and 1864.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet became highly popular as a social pastime in England during the 1860s.
[src:cornhole/croquet] It was enthusiastically adopted and promoted by the Earl of Essex, who held lavish croquet parties at Cassiobury House, his stately home in Watford, Hertfordshire, and the Earl even launched his own *Cassiobury* brand croquet set.
[src:cornhole/croquet] By 1867, Jaques had printed 65,000 copies of his *Laws and Regulations* of the game.
[src:cornhole/croquet] It quickly spread to other Anglophone countries, including Australia, Canada, New Zealand, South Africa, and the United States.
[src:cornhole/croquet] No doubt one of the attractions was that the game could be played by both sexes; this also ensured a certain amount of adverse comment.
[src:cornhole/croquet] It is no coincidence that the game became popular at the same time as the cylinder lawn mower, since croquet can only be played well on a lawn that is flat and finely-cut.
[src:cornhole/croquet] By the late 1870s, however, croquet had been eclipsed by another fashionable game, lawn tennis, and many of the newly created croquet clubs, including the All England Club at Wimbledon, converted some or all of their lawns into tennis courts.
[src:cornhole/croquet] There was a revival in the 1890s, but going forward croquet was always a minority sport, with national individual participation amounting to a few thousand players.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club still has a croquet lawn, but has not hosted any significant tournaments.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Its championship was won 38 times by Bernard Neal.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The English headquarters for the game is now in Cheltenham.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The earliest known reference to croquet in Scotland is the booklet *The Game of Croquet, its Laws and Regulations*, which was published in the mid-1860s for the proprietor of Eglinton Castle, the Earl of Eglinton.
[src:cornhole/croquet] On the page facing the title page is a picture of Eglinton Castle with a game of "croquet" in full swing.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The croquet lawn existed on the northern terrace, between Eglinton Castle and the Lugton Water.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The 13th Earl developed a variation on croquet named Captain Moreton's Eglinton Castle croquet, which had small bells on the eight hoops "to ring the changes", two pegs, a double hoop with a bell, and two tunnels for the ball to pass through.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In 1865, the 'Rules of the Eglinton Castle and Cassiobury Croquet' was published by Edmund Routledge.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Several incomplete sets of this form of croquet are known to exist, and one complete set is still used for demonstration games in the West of Scotland.
[src:cornhole/croquet] An imaginary line on which a ball is placed for its first shot in the game, or when taking a lift: The A-baulk coincides with the western half of the yard line along the south boundary; the B-baulk occupies the eastern half of the north boundary yard line.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A bisque is a free turn in a handicap match.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A half-bisque is a restricted handicap turn in which no point may be scored.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In association croquet, a shot which results after a roqueted ball comes to rest in contact with another ball on the lawn: The laws allow for this third ball to also be moved on the resulting croquet stroke, staying in touch with the roqueted ball (on which the striker is now ball-in-hand).
[src:cornhole/croquet] The croquet stroke with the three balls in contact is referred to as a "cannon".
[src:cornhole/croquet] : Corner cannons occur a good deal more frequently than other cannons because skilled players seek them out as a way of getting a ball out of a corner and into a break.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The corner is a fairly large target into which to rush and set up a corner cannon.
[src:cornhole/croquet] : This is done by using primary colours and secondary colours.
[src:cornhole/croquet] When the two games impinge on each other players mark the balls to allow the other game to proceed.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The main croquet ball colours used are blue, red, black and yellow.
[src:cornhole/croquet] One player or team plays blue and black, the other red and yellow.
[src:cornhole/croquet] : When the striker's ball hits a ball with which the player is entitled to then take a croquet shot, it is a roquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] At the start of a turn, the striker is entitled to roquet all the other three balls once.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Once the striker's ball goes through its target hoop, the player is again entitled to roquet the other balls once.
[src:cornhole/croquet] A roquet when the roqueted ball is sent to a specific position on the court, such as the next hoop for the striker's ball or close to a ball that the striker wishes to roquet next.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The colours of the balls used in the second game played on the same court in double-banking are green, pink, brown and white.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Green and brown versus pink and white, are played by the same player or pair.
[src:cornhole/croquet] (TPO), where the opponent's ball, rather than the partner ball, is peeled.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The significance of this manoeuvre is that in advanced play, making a break that includes the tenth hoop (called 4-back) is penalized by granting the opponent a lift (entitling him to take the next shot from either baulk line).
[src:cornhole/croquet] Therefore, many breaks stop voluntarily with three hoops and the peg still to run.
[src:cornhole/croquet] When a hoop or the peg impedes the path of a striker's ball, or the swing of the mallet, a player will often endeavour to finish a turn with the opponent's balls wired from each other.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet is popularly believed to be viciously competitive.
[src:cornhole/croquet] That may derive from the fact that (unlike in golf) players will often attempt to move their opponents' balls to unfavourable positions.
[src:cornhole/croquet] However, purely negative play is rarely a winning strategy; successful players (in all versions other than golf croquet) will use all four balls to set up a break for themselves, rather than simply making the game as difficult as possible for their opponents.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The way croquet is depicted in paintings and books says much about popular perceptions of the game, though little about the reality of modern play.
[src:cornhole/croquet] About 200 croquet clubs across the United States are members of the United States Croquet Association.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Many colleges have croquet clubs as well, such as The University of Virginia, The University of Chicago, Pennsylvania State University, Bates College, SUNY New Paltz, Harvard University, and Dartmouth College.
[src:cornhole/croquet] John's College and the US Naval Academy engage in a yearly match in Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Both schools also compete at the collegiate level and the rivalry continues to be an Annapolis tradition, attracting thousands of spectators each April.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In England and Wales, there are over 200 clubs affiliated with Croquet England.
[src:cornhole/croquet] The All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club at Wimbledon is famous for its lawn tennis tournament, but retains an active croquet section.
[src:cornhole/croquet] There are clubs in many universities and colleges, with an annual varsity match being played between Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:cornhole/croquet] With over 1800 participants, the 2011 Oxford University "Cuppers" (inter-college) tournament claimed to be not only the largest croquet tournament ever, but the largest sporting event in the university's history.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Australia has croquet clubs in every state with about 10,000 players.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet Australia is the national body with each State having its own Association.
[src:cornhole/croquet] In Spain there are 37 clubs federated to the Federación Española de Croquet.
[src:cornhole/croquet] Croquet is a growing sport in Spain with 4 new clubs joining the FEC in 2024.
[src:cornhole/croquet] There are 112 clubs in New Zealand, affiliated with 19 associations.
[src:cornhole/croquet] They are governed by Croquet New Zealand.
[src:cornhole/drano] Sodium nitrate reacts with hydrogen gas: Na+ + NO3− + 4H2 → NaOH + NH3 + 2H2O.
[src:cornhole/drano] This removes hydrogen, which poses a fire and explosion hazard and produces ammonia, which is also capable of decomposing organic material, albeit less aggressively than lye.
[src:cornhole/drano] The sodium hydroxide (lye) is consumed by further action of the first reaction.
[src:cornhole/drano] Crystal Drano was invented in 1923 by Harry Drackett.
[src:cornhole/drano] From the 1960s into the 1980s, Drackett advertised *Once in every week, Drano in every drain*.
[src:cornhole/drano] Bristol-Myers bought the Drackett Company in 1965 and sold it to S.
[src:cornhole/drano] Drano has been developed into several forms; as of 2016, the original *Crystal Drano* is marketed as *Drano Kitchen Crystals Clog Remover*.
[src:cornhole/drano] Drano Aerosol Plunger was developed in the late 1960s, intended as a safer product that would be kinder environmentally.
[src:cornhole/drano] It was basically just a can of CFC propellant, the best-known brand of which was Freon.
[src:cornhole/drano] After Earth Day in 1970, there came increasing pressure to eliminate CFC propellants.
[src:cornhole/drano] Drackett used cheaper propellants, a blend of propane and butane, in all its other products.
[src:cornhole/drano] However, the propellant mix created a fire hazard.
[src:cornhole/drano] The forceful propellant required most consumers use both hands to control the can, plus another hand or two to hold a rag over the drain vent to contain the pressure.
[src:cornhole/drano] The pressure sometimes knocked apart poor plumbing without blasting free the clog.
[src:cornhole/drano] Consumers who ignored instructions and attempted to use chemical drain openers first could be chemically burned from blow-back.
[src:cornhole/drano] Liquid Drano was introduced in response to Clorox's purchase of Liquid-Plumr in 1969.
[src:cornhole/drano] Originally, it was simply a liquid lye (sodium hydroxide).
[src:cornhole/drano] In the late 1970s, the product was reformulated as a combination of liquid lye and sodium hypochlorite.
[src:cornhole/drano] Sodium hypochlorite is used in low (5%) concentration as laundry bleach and in higher concentrations as a swimming pool disinfectant.
[src:cornhole/drano] Liquid Drano is marketed in several forms, including Drano Liquid Clog Remover, Drano Max Build-Up Remover, and Drano Dual-Force Foamer Clog Remover.
[src:cornhole/drano] All are variations on the basic Liquid Drano formula.
[src:cornhole/drano] Drano Foamer first started out a powder similar to Crystal Drano in which water had to be added.
[src:cornhole/drano] This was the first-ever foaming pipe snake product.
[src:cornhole/drano] This caused Liquid-Plumr to launch Liquid-Plumr: Foaming Pipe Snake, which is a 2-in-1 liquid.
[src:cornhole/drano] Many years later, the makers of Drano decided to reimagine Drano Foamer as a 2-in-1 liquid known as the Dual Force Foamer.
[src:cornhole/drano] The Drano Snake Plus Drain Cleaning Kit combines a mechanical snake for loosening clogs, with yet another gel-variation on the Liquid Drano formula.
[src:cornhole/drano] Drano has been used to create homemade bombs called *Drano bombs* by mixing the product with aluminum.
[src:cornhole/drano] In 2017, a Drano bomb severely burned a 12-year-old girl in the neighborhood of Harlem in New York City.
[src:cornhole/drano] Drano bombs have the ability to cause third-degree burns and blindness.
[src:cornhole/drano] After watching the film *Magnum Force* (1973), in which a prostitute is shown immediately dying after being forced to drink Drano, former United States Air Force airmen Dale Selby Pierre and William Andrews decided it would be an efficient method of murder in their crime.
[src:cornhole/drano] However, the hostages did not instantly die after being forced to drink the cleaning product.
[src:cornhole/drano] Angered by this, Pierre and Andrews decided to shoot three of them, and attempted to strangle the fourth.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The **grade** (US) or **gradient** (UK) (also called **slope**, **incline**, **mainfall**, **pitch** or **rise**) of a physical feature, landform or constructed line is either the elevation angle of that surface to the horizontal or its tangent.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] It is a special case of the slope, where zero indicates horizontality.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] A larger number indicates higher or steeper degree of "tilt".
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Often slope is calculated as a ratio of "rise" to "run", or as a fraction ("rise over run") in which *run* is the horizontal distance (not the distance along the slope) and *rise* is the vertical distance.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Slopes of existing physical features such as canyons and hillsides, stream and river banks, and beds are often described as grades, but typically the word "grade" is used for human-made surfaces such as roads, landscape grading, roof pitches, railroads, aqueducts, and pedestrian or bicycle routes.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The grade may refer to the longitudinal slope or the perpendicular cross slope.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] 2. as a *percentage*, the formula for which is $100\times {\frac {\text{rise}}{\text{run}}}$ , which is equivalent to the tangent of the angle of inclination times 100.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] At a slope angle of 45 degrees, the run is equal to the rise.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Expressed as a percentage, the slope of this angle is 100 percent.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] As the slope approaches 90 degrees (vertical), the percentage slope approaches infinity.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In Europe and the U.S. percentage *grade* is the most commonly used figure for describing slopes.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] 3. as a *‰* figure (denoted with the symbol ‰), the formula for which is $1000\times {\frac {\text{rise}}{\text{run}}}$ , which could also be expressed as *the tangent of the angle of inclination times 1000*.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] This is commonly used in Europe to denote the incline of a railway.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] It is sometimes written using *mm/m* or *m/km* instead of the ‰ symbol.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] 4. as a *ratio* of one part rise to so many parts run.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] For example, a slope that has a rise of 5 feet for every 1000 feet of run would have a slope ratio of 1 in 200.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] (The word *in* is normally used rather than the mathematical ratio notation of e.g.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] *1:200*.) This is generally the method used to describe railway grades in Australia and the UK.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] It is used for roads in Hong Kong, and was used for roads in the UK until the 1970s.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] 5. as a *ratio* of many parts run to one part rise, which is the inverse of the previous expression (depending on the country and the industry standards).
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] For example, a slope expressed as *4:1* in this system means for a given vertical distance the horizontal distance travelled is four times as long.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] When the term *grade* is used, the slope is usually expressed as a percentage.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] If one looks at red numbers on the chart specifying grade, one can see the quirkiness of using the grade to specify slope; the numbers go from 0 for flat, to 100% at 45 degrees, to infinity at vertical.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Slope may still be expressed when the horizontal run is not known: the rise can be divided by the hypotenuse (the slope length).
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] This is not the usual way to specify slope; this nonstandard expression follows the sine function rather than the tangent function, so it calls a 45 degree slope a 71 percent grade instead of a 100 percent.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] But in practice the usual way to calculate slope is to measure the distance along the slope and the vertical rise, and calculate the horizontal run from that, in order to calculate the grade (100% × rise/run) or standard slope (rise/run).
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] When the angle of inclination is small, using the slope length rather than the horizontal displacement (i.e., using the sine of the angle rather than the tangent) makes only an insignificant difference and can then be used as an approximation.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Railway gradients are often expressed in terms of the rise in relation to the distance along the track as a practical measure.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In cases where the difference between sin and tan is significant, the tangent is used.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In either case, the following identity holds for all inclinations up to 90 degrees: $\tan {\alpha }={\frac {\sin {\alpha }}{\sqrt {1-\sin ^{2}{\alpha }}}}$ .
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Or more simply, one can calculate the horizontal run by using the Pythagorean theorem, after which it is trivial to calculate the (standard math) slope or the grade (percentage).
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In Europe, road gradients are expressed in signage as percentage.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Grades are related using the following equations with symbols from the figure at top.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] For degrees, percentage (%) and per-mille (‰) notations, larger numbers are steeper slopes.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] For ratios, larger numbers *n* of 1 in *n* are shallower, easier slopes.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The examples show round numbers in one or more of the notations and some documented and reasonably well known instances.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In vehicular engineering, various land-based designs (automobiles, sport utility vehicles, trucks, trains, etc.) are rated for their ability to ascend terrain.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Trains typically rate much lower than automobiles.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The highest grade a vehicle can ascend while maintaining a particular speed is sometimes termed that vehicle's "gradeability" (or, less often, "grade ability").
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The lateral slopes of a highway geometry are sometimes called fills or cuts where these techniques have been used to create them.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The steepest roads in the world according to the Guinness Book of World Records are Baldwin Street in Dunedin, New Zealand, Ffordd Pen Llech in Harlech, Wales and Canton Avenue in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The Guinness World Record once again lists Baldwin Street as the steepest street in the world, with a 34.8% grade (1 in 2.87) after a successful appeal against the ruling that handed the title, briefly, to Ffordd Pen Llech.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] A number of streets elsewhere have steeper grades than those listed in the Guinness Book.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] National Elevation Dataset, 7x7 (magazine) identified ten blocks of public streets in San Francisco open to vehicular traffic in the city with grades over 30 percent.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The steepest, at 41 percent, is the block of Bradford Street above Tompkins Avenue in the Bernal Heights neighborhood.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The San Francisco Municipal Railway operates bus service among the city's hills.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The steepest grade for bus operations is 23.1% by the *67 Bernal Heights* on Alabama Street between Ripley and Esmeralda Streets.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Likewise, the Pittsburgh Department of Engineering and Construction recorded a grade of 37% (20°) for Canton Avenue.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] The street has formed part of a bicycle race since 1983.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Grade, pitch, and slope are important components in landscape design, garden design, landscape architecture, and architecture for engineering and aesthetic design factors.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Drainage, slope stability, circulation of people and vehicles, complying with building codes, and design integration are all aspects of slope considerations in environmental design.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Ruling gradients limit the load that a locomotive can haul, including the weight of the locomotive itself.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Pulling a heavily loaded train at 20 km/h may require ten times the force climbing a 1% slope than on level track.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Early railways in the United Kingdom were laid out with very gentle gradients, such as 0.07575% (1 in 1320) and 0.1515% (1 in 660) on the Great Western main line, nicknamed Brunel's Billiard Table, because the early locomotives (and their brakes) were feeble.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Steep gradients were concentrated in short sections of lines where it was convenient to employ assistant engines or cable haulage, such as the 1.2-kilometre (0.75-mile) section from Euston to Camden Town.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Extremely steep gradients require mechanical assistance.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Cable systems are used in cases like the Scenic Railway at Katoomba Scenic World in Australia, which reaches a maximum grade of 122% (52°) and is claimed to be the world's steepest passenger-carrying funicular.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] For somewhat gentler inclines, rack railways are employed, such as the Pilatus Railway in Switzerland, which has a maximum grade of 48% (26°) and is considered the steepest rack railway.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Gradients can be expressed as an angle, as feet per mile, feet per chain, 1 in n, x% or y per mille.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Since designers like round figures, the method of expression can affect the gradients selected.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] Gradients on sharp curves are effectively a bit steeper than the same gradient on straight track, so to compensate for this and make the ruling grade uniform throughout, the gradient on those sharp curves should be reduced slightly.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In the era before they were provided with continuous brakes, whether air brakes or vacuum brakes, steep gradients made it extremely difficult for trains to stop safely.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] In those days, for example, an inspector insisted that Rudgwick railway station in West Sussex be regraded.
[src:cornhole/grade-slope] He would not allow it to open until the gradient through the platform was eased from 1 in 80 to 1 in 130.
